  {
   "kind": 1,
   "value": "(*Section M final report — the r=0 ANCHOR closes exactly (uniquely); the GENERAL (p,r) ansatz, as\nliterally stated, does NOT close under any of the four specified escalation variants, and a precise\nrank/dimension-counting argument shows WHY no finite extension of the θ1-tower can ever fix it.\nReported precisely per instruction (\"report which variant closes\"): none did, with the exact\ndiagnostic evidence below.\n\nSETUP. O[p,r] := O2rot[λ1,λ2][M,n][-p,-r] (sign convention φ(k)=-k, matching Section F/I). Target\nansatz: O[p,r] = Σ_{s=0}^S c_s(p,r) · Q1(θ1+sh)/Q1(θ1), c_s state-independent within a rep. Since\nthe \"measurement matrix\" columns Q1(θ1+sh)/Q1(θ1) (indexed by s) do NOT depend on (p,r) — only on\nthe rep and state — the machinery was built ONCE per (rep,S) and solved via LeastSquares against\nmany (p,r) samples, exact-rational sample points throughout.\n\nR=0 ANCHOR — CLOSES EXACTLY, UNIQUELY. With S=λ1 (the natural range for this limit), rep (2,1),\np=7/3: the solved c_s EXACTLY matches Section F's known single-rotation weights,\nc_s = w1[λ1][[s+1]]·(-p)^s (w1[λ] = br1's tower weights, {1,-1} for λ=1, {1,-2,1} for λ=2, etc.),\nresidual literal 0 (Cell 165). The 6x3 measurement matrix has rank 3 = number of unknowns, so the\nkernel is TRIVIAL (0-dimensional) — the solution is unique, not a family (Cell 171). This confirms\nthe Opr/towerMat machinery itself is correct before diagnosing the general case.\n\nGENERAL (p,r), r≠0 — FAILS, ROBUSTLY, ACROSS ALL FOUR ESCALATION VARIANTS TESTED:\n  - Natural range S=λ1+λ2 (Paul's specified starting point): residual 27.68 (rep (2,1), sample\n    p=7/3,r=5/2) — large, not numerical noise (30+ digit precision throughout). Confirmed at 4\n    MORE independent (p,r) samples (residuals 4.0, 8.9, 39.3, 5.3 — Cell 169) and a second rep\n    (1,2) (residual 27.94 — Cell 169): a robust, reproducible failure, not a fluke of one sample.\n  - Variant (a), extended range: scanned s-windows from S=λ1+λ2 up to λ1+λ2+4 (Cell 164) AND\n    shifted/negative-offset windows sMin from -4 to 0 with various widths (Cell 167) — the\n    achievable column-space RANK STAYS FIXED AT 4 (=λ1+λ2+1) no matter how the window is chosen;\n    residual is UNCHANGED (27.68 to 15+ digits) for every window tried. No extension helps.\n  - Variant (b), alternative normalization: tried dividing by Q1(θ1)Q1(θ2) (residual 18.31) and\n    multiplying by Q1(θ2) (residual 19.76) instead of the plain Q1(θ1) target (Cell 168) — both\n    still large, no improvement.\n  - Variant (c), tower on θ2 instead of θ1: residual 25.42 (Cell 166) — no improvement.\n  - Variant (d), state-independent prefactor: a prefactor that is state-independent by definition\n    can only RESCALE the target vector's magnitude, not change which DIRECTION in state-space it\n    points — it cannot move a vector genuinely outside a subspace into that subspace, so this\n    variant cannot help by construction (not separately numerically tested, since the argument is\n    exact linear algebra: rescaling commutes through the whole system).\n  - Extra check: bare polynomial basis q1(θ1+sh)/q1(θ1) (no κ1^(u/h) prefactor at all, testing\n    whether \"handle κ1 bookkeeping explicitly\" meant using the bare tower) gives an IDENTICAL\n    residual (27.68, Cell 170) — expected, since replacing Q1 by q1 is just an invertible\n    per-column rescaling by κ1^s, which cannot change the achievable column space's rank or\n    direction (confirmed directly rather than assumed).\n\nTHE PRECISE REASON (dimension count, not a numerical artifact): for a FIXED state, Q1(θ1+sh)\n= κ1^(θ1/h+s) q_1(θ1+sh) with q_1 a polynomial of degree M (the state's own weight-sector label).\nSampling q_1 at ANY number of points s only ever spans an (M+1)-dimensional space of information\n(Lagrange/Vandermonde) — extra samples beyond M+1 points add NOTHING new. Stacking all states of a\nrep, the ACHIEVABLE column space of the θ1-tower (over ANY, even infinite, choice of s) is capped\nat rank = max_state(M+1) = λ1+λ2+1 exactly, independent of window (numerically confirmed: rank\nstuck at 4 for both (2,1) and (1,2), matching λ1+λ2+1=4 in both cases). This is EXACTLY Paul's own\nspecified starting range S=0..λ1+λ2 — so the \"natural\" range is already the best ANY θ1-tower\nconstruction can ever do; escalating further is mathematically incapable of adding rank. Since\nO[p,r] (r≠0) has a component strictly outside this maximal 4-dimensional subspace (a robust,\nmulti-sample, multi-rep numerical fact, not a rounding artifact), NO state-independent linear\ncombination of Q1 values at θ1-tower points — of any length, offset, or (invertible) normalization\n— can reproduce it. This is a hard obstruction to the single-θ1-tower ansatz as literally stated,\nnot merely \"not yet found within the tested variants.\"\n\nWHAT MIGHT RECONCILE THIS WITH PAUL'S CERTAINTY (flagged, not pursued further — outside the\nspecified exact-linear-algebra escalation list): the obstruction is specifically about a LINEAR\ncombination of plain Q1 EVALUATIONS at integer θ1-tower points. Possibilities not tested here: (i)\nthe tower entries might need to be DERIVATIVES of Q1 at θ1 (not just values) — this would add new\nindependent directions beyond the M+1 cap since Wronskian-type data isn't capped by polynomial\ndegree the same way; (ii) c_s might need to depend on the STATE after all through a \"hidden\"\nκ1-power that isn't state-independent in the way tested (e.g. if Paul's E21 acts with a different\nnormalization on site 2, introducing state-dependent structure into what looks like a\nstate-independent c_s here); (iii) the ansatz might hold only after also correcting by the SAME\nkind of level-graded recoupling (Section K's B matrix) rather than a flat sum — i.e. c_s itself\nmight secretly need to be a sum over an AUXILIARY index tied to r's own expansion, not a single\nnumber per s. None of these were tested; they are structurally different constructions from what\nwas specified, so per instruction this is reported as the precise gate/variant-failure data rather\nthan pursued as new invented alternatives.*)",
   "languageId": "markdown",
   "outputs": [],
   "metadata": {}
  },
  {
   "kind": 1,
   "value": "(*REDIRECT — Paul supplied his own working formula (su(2), his eq. 238-239, ℓ=1,L=2, β=α=1):\n  (⟨↑|e^{σS+}⊗⟨↑|e^{αS+})|Ψ⟩ = (1/N_1^γ)Λ^{-1}⟨e^{(γ-φ)u}u^{β-1}Q(u)⟩_α,\n  σ=α(e^{iγ}-1)/(e^{iγ}-e^{2iφ}), Λ=(1-e^{-iγ}e^{2iφ})/(1-e^{2iφ}).\nRepo-convention target: O[p,r] := (⟨x0[λ1]|e^{pE21}⊗⟨x0[λ2]|e^{rE21}).Psi = C(T,r)·br1[λ1][T^{u/h}Q1],\nT a NEW free parameter, C state-independent, p=P(T,r) an unknown coupling — solve for both by\nEXACT LINEAR ALGEBRA: for fixed (T,r), O[p,r][state] is a KNOWN polynomial in p; br1[T^uQ1][state]\n=FL[λ1,λ2][state][T] is a KNOWN NUMBER once T is fixed (FL already defined, Section F Cell 67).\nSince O[p,r][state]/FL[state](T) must equal the SAME C(T,r) for every state, cross-state ratios\neliminate C and give a polynomial equation in p alone per pair of states; consistency across ALL\npairs is the hard verification. This supersedes the brute-force free-c_s linear solve of the\nun-redirected Section M (kept above as the negative-result record motivating this reformulation —\nnote explicitly BELOW where c_s = C(T,r)·w1[λ1]·T^s reproduces those numbers).*)",
   "languageId": "markdown",
   "outputs": [],
   "metadata": {}
  },
  {
   "kind": 2,
   "value": "(*Cross-state elimination of C: for FIXED (T,r), solve O[p,r][state_i]·FL[state_j](T) =\n  O[p,r][state_j]·FL[state_i](T) for p, using ONE pair, then check ALL OTHER pairs give the SAME p.*)\nClearAll[solveCoupling];\nsolveCoupling[λ1_,λ2_][T_,r_] := Module[{states,FLvals,Ovals,eqs,sols,pCandidates},\n  states = statesOf[λ1,λ2];\n  FLvals = Table[FL[λ1,λ2][st[[1]],st[[2]]][T], {st,states}];\n  Ovals = Table[Opr[λ1,λ2][st[[1]],st[[2]]][p,r], {st,states}];\n  (*use state 1 as reference, solve p from pairing with every other state*)\n  pCandidates = Table[\n    Module[{eq,sol},\n      eq = Ovals[[1]] FLvals[[i]] - Ovals[[i]] FLvals[[1]] == 0;\n      sol = NSolve[eq, p, WorkingPrecision->30];\n      {i, states[[i]], p/.sol}\n    ]\n  ,{i,2,Length[states]}];\n  pCandidates\n];\n(*rep (2,1), T=7/3, r=5/2 sample.*)\npCand21 = solveCoupling[2,1][7/3,5/2];\npCand21 // TableForm",
   "languageId": "wolfram",
   "outputs": [
